<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Square Box Example</title>
    <style>
        #box {
            width: 300px;
            height: 300px;
            background-color: red;
            transition: all 0.3s ease;
            cursor: pointer;
            border-radius: 2px;
        }
    </style>

</head>
<body>
    <div id="box"></div>
    <script>
        var box = document.getElementById('box');

        box.addEventListener('click', function() {
            box.style.backgroundColor = 'yellow';
            box.style.width = '600px';
            box.style.height = '600px';
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>

<!--
    In this code, we have an input box (<input>) and a submit button (<button>) wrapped in a container (<div>). 
        
    The list (<ul>) with the id "text-list" is placed below the input box. We use CSS to style the elements accordingly.

    In JavaScript, we use getElementById() to get references to the input box, submit button, and text list. 
    
    We then attach a click event listener to the submit button using addEventListener(). 
    
    Inside the event handler function, we get the value of the input box using the value property and create a new list item (<li>) element. 
        
    We set the text content of the list item to the input text and append it to the text list using appendChild(). 
        
    Finally, we clear the input box by setting its value to an empty string.
-->
